bib_record.title: Measurements of neutron elastic scattering from carbon in the energy region of 0.50 to 2.00 MeV.

free_txt: differential data on listings.
The 3 MeV Van de Graaff of CBNM,
proton beam pulse width = 1 ns,
repetition rate = 1 MHz.
.The variation in the target neutron yields as a
function of angle and energy due to the finite target-
to-sample geometry,
.Attenuation of the incoming neutron flux and
multiple scattering in the samples using the program
MAGGIE.
.Phase shift analysis done,
.Legendre polynomial expansion done,
.integration of this expansion and fitting of the
integral cross section to a power series in the
neutron energy (E) leads to the empirical expression
with E in MeV, valid between 0.50 and 2.00 MeV.
3 Cylindrical NE102A plastic scintillator
detectors 5.0 cm * 2.5 cm, each viewed by an AVP56/03
photomultiplier, a fourth detector used for monitoring
the neutron flux from the target.
Total error around 2.8% includes:
Uncertainty in detector efficiency
Uncertainty in total n-p scattering
cross-section
Uncertainty in counting statistics on H
Uncertainty in alpha-factor in CH2
Uncertainty in H-content in CH2
Multiple scattering correction in carbon
Uncertainty in flux factor in C-sample consists:
1) due to fluctuations in flux calculations
2) due to uncertainties of Sig-T
In evaluating the errors to the individual experimental
points, the ones introduced by the counting statistics
and those originating from the statistical nature of
the Monte Carlo method were considered.
The 3 MeV Van de Graaff of CBNM,
proton beam pulse width = 1 ns,
repetition rate = 1 MHz.
Total neutron energy spread between 30 and 45 keV.
Time of flight path = 141.0 cm,
overall resolution 2.3 ns.
Distance target-sample = 15.0 cm in the direction of
the proton beam, the 3 detectors collimated towards
the sample can be positioned at different angles but
at equal distance 141.0 cm from the sample.
Polyethylene sample used. The hydrogeneous sample was
a polyethylene cylinder of 1.00 cm outside diameter,
0.60 cm inside diameter and 4.00 cm height. Its weight
was 1.840 g and the content of hydrogen was 14.31%.
Cylindrical carbon samples, dimensions given
in Subents.
Data taken from private communication.
